# Python Standards

## Purpose
Define Python 3.11+ coding standards for maintainable, testable AI Engineering code.

## Rules
- Use Python 3.11+ features when they improve clarity.
- Prefer small, typed, testable functions.
- Use explicit function return types.
- Avoid hidden global state.
- Keep modules focused on one responsibility.
- Prefer standard library solutions before adding dependencies.
- Use `pathlib.Path` for filesystem paths.
- Use Pydantic models for API and configuration data.
- Use dataclasses only for simple internal value objects.
- Avoid broad `except Exception` unless adding context and re-raising or converting to a domain error.

## Structure Guidance
- Put reusable application code under `app/` for this exercise.
- Put HTTP endpoints under `app/routers/`.
- Put business and provider logic under `app/services/`.
- Put static prompt/context examples under `app/context/`.
- Put experiments under `notebooks/` or `experiments/` only when needed.
- Do not leave business logic only in notebooks.

## Example
```python
from pathlib import Path


def load_prompt(path: Path) -> str:
    return path.read_text(encoding="utf-8")
```

## Checklist
- [ ] Functions have clear names and return types.
- [ ] Business logic is reusable outside notebooks.
- [ ] Dependencies are justified.
- [ ] No hardcoded local paths.
- [ ] Modules have one clear reason to change.

